definition.value: This is an AE which is paralysis of the ciliary muscle of the eye, resulting in a loss of accommodation.
This is an AE which is  refraction paralysis of the ciliary muscle of the eye, resulting in a loss of accommodation.
This is an AE which is a pathology affecting the cornea.
This is an AE which is a rare, benign yet relapsing pustular dermatosis.
This is an AE which is a condition with varicella in which the eye's cornea, the clear dome on the front surface of the eye, becomes inflamed.
This is an AE which can be a serious threat to vision if not treated appropriately and in a timely fashion.
This is an AE which is a condition that results in the loss of eyelashes, and sometimes eyebrows.
This is an AE which is a medical term for abnormally positioned eyelashes that grow back toward the eye, touching the cornea or conjunctiva.

This is an AE which is a part of the eye that includes the ciliary muscle, which controls the shape of the lens, and the ciliary epithelium, which produces the aqueous humor and its function becomes disorder.
This is an AE which is the increase of blood flow to different tissues in the ciliary.
This is an AE which is a sudden involuntary contraction of  ciliary muscle muscle.
This is an AE which is one of the hairs that grows at the edge of the eyelids.

This is an AE which is a rare, ciliopathic, autosomal recessive genetic disorder that causes defects in the action of cilia lining the respiratory tract (lower and upper, sinuses, Eustachian tube, middle ear), fallopian tube, and flagellum of sperm cells.
This is an AE which has also been observed in normal aging eyes.
This is an AE which is a condition of the eye in which the vitreous membrane separates from the retina.
This is an AE which refers a clear gel that fills the space between the lens and the retina in vertebrate eyes and its function becomes disorder.
This is an AE which is sometimes visible deposits within the eye's vitreous humour ("the vitreous"), which is normally transparent, or between the vitreous and retina.
This is an AE which refers a layer of collagen separating the vitreous body from the rest of the eye and it is haze.

This is an AE which can be classified according to their aetiology as: genetic; inflammatory non-infectious; inflammatory infectious; inflammatory iatrogenic; degenerative, traumatic; neoplastic and idiopathic.

This is an AE which is a common and reliable finding of brain herniation, ischaemia, and acute brain injury in critically ill patients.
This is an AE which refers the  diagnosis of an afferent or efferent it  is crucial in the acquisition of a broad range of diseases of the brain or the peripheral nervous system.
This is an AE which is determined using dynamic pupillometry and is impaired.
This is an AE which is blood escaping from the circulatory system from damaged scleral  blood vessels.
This is an AE which is the build-up of fluid in the scleral tissue.
This is an AE which is a benign, self-limiting inflammatory disease affecting part of the eye called the episclera.
This is an AE which is a serious inflammatory disease that affects the white outer coating of the eye, known as the sclera.
This is an AE which consisted of cortical dots of various shapes that increased in number with the age of the carriers in older obligate carriers, subcapsular plaques were common.
This is an AE which is a sudden involuntary contraction of a muscle when nictitating.
This is an AE which is a fold or line in the skin below the lower eyelid.

This is an AE which is typical manifestations of systemic diseases (e. g. Graves' disease) or typical complications of diseases in the vicinity of the orbit (e. g. orbital complications from inflammatory or tumorous sinus diseases).
This is an AE which is the product of a mismatch between the axial length of the eye and its optical power, creating blurred vision.
This is an AE which is vision loss or weakness that occurs without an apparent lesion affecting the eye.
This is an AE which is the aqueous humor-filled space inside the eye between the iris and the cornea's innermost surface, the endothelium.
This is an AE which is the aqueous humor-filled space inside the eye between the iris and the cornea's innermost surface  and it has  inflammation.
This is an AE which is a rare, late complication of cataract surgery, associated with impairment of visual function.
This is an AE which is a type of refractive error due to rotational asymmetry in the eye's refractive power.
This is an AE which refers difficulty seeing in the presence of very bright light.
This is an AE which is the most common complication after cataract surgery, with an incidence of 30%.
This is an AE which is a rare benign neuroepithelial intraventricular WHO grade I lesion found in the choroid plexus.
This is an AE which is a prevalent and potentially vision-threatening complication following glaucoma surgery.
This is an AE which is an inflammation of the choroid (thin pigmented vascular coat of the eye) and retina of the eye.
This is an AE which is a closed  macular sac, having a distinct envelope and division compared with the nearby tissue.
This is an AE which is formation of the fibrous tissue in place of the normal retinal tissue on the macular area of the retina which provides the sharpest vision in the eyes.

This is an AE which is a pathological wound healing in which connective tissue replaces normal parenchymal tissue to the extent that it goes unchecked, leading to considerable tissue remodelling and the formation of permanent scar tissue such as macular fibrosis.
This is an AE which is a small break in the macula, located in the center of the eye's light-sensitive tissue called the retina.
This is an AE which occurs when fluid and protein deposits collect on or under the macula of the eye (a yellow central area of the retina) and causes it to thicken and swell (edema).

This is an AE which is a polygenic phenotypic character determined by two distinct factors: the pigmentation of the eye's iris and the frequency-dependence of the scattering of light by the turbid medium in the stroma of the iris.
This is an AE which is supposed to be different from that of macular lamellar hole (LMH) and is thought to be caused by centripetal contraction of previously present epiretinal membrane.
This is an AE which is any pathological condition of the macula, an area at the centre of the retina that is associated with highly sensitive, accurate vision.
